commitResults.messageTitle: Add tag adding and editing functionality
commitResults.messageBody:
Users are unable to tag a dengue case with the associated dengue variant.

Adding dengue variant tags will allow for more granular analysis of the commonness of different dengue strains in Singapore, and enable quick action should a particular strain that residents are less immune to become unusually common.

Let’s add the ability to add and edit tags that will indicate the dengue variant associated with each dengue case.

Using an enum will allow us to easily validate that only actual dengue variants are used as tags compared to using regex or a list of accepted input.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add method to StringUtil to accomodate substring searches for "find"
commitResults.messageBody:
The original find command uses containsWordIgnoreCase, which only
accepts full-word searches.

However, when we want to search names, we may not recall the full name.
For example, we may remember Bernice as "Bern..."

Therefore, as a step to more efficient searches, we will check if the
search is a substring of the full name first.

commitResults.messageBody:
Instead of just being able to search by name, the user should be able to
search for dengue cases by postal codes. In this case, it would be good
to search for postal codes which start with a certain index.
Additionally, it is essential to consider postal codes which do not
simply contain a certain sequence of numbers, as this may cause too few
results to be filtered

Edit the date class to accept new formats for dates Dates should adhere to the following constraints:
commitResults.messageBody:
Dates to contain 4-digit years YYYY, 2-digit days and either 2-digit
months MM, 3-letter months MMM, or fully-spelled months MMMM.
Special characters may now be allowed (no longer dashes to separate YYYY
from MM), and the ordering of data will not matter unless the data is
ambiguous. (See below)
If months are given in the MM format and the dates are ambiguous, eg.
20001010, YYYY will be read first, followed by MM and DD.
If months are given in MMM or MMMM formats, months will be read first,
eg. march 20 10 february will be read as march
Dates must be valid. i.e. MM must be a number between 01 and 12
inclusive, dd must be a number between 01 and 31 inclusive
dd should be within the valid range for the MM given
